   112	  One other concern has been expressed by some program authors, those authors
   113	who have desired not to have their programs modified but whose programs have
   114	nonetheless been modified.
   115	
   116	  Referring to the discussion above about the limitations on use of contributed
   117	programs, if the limitation did not authorize anything but "use" of the program,
   118	then the modifications constituted "derivative" works that were not authorized.
   119	This, unfortunately, would be a very tricky thing to prove, and it would have to
   120	be proved - how did the parties understand the authorization to use the programs
   121	(ie, was modification prevented but noncommercial use allowed?).  If there was
   122	an implied license to modify (for example, because the program was included with
   123	other programs in which modifications were explicitly authorized), it might be
   124	very difficult to prove infringement under either the state or federal law,
   125	depending on which was applicable.
   126	
   127	  It should be clear from the above, however, that modifications of programs
   128	entitled to copyright protection are infringements if they are not authorized by
   129	the owner of the copyright in the original program.  The problem is in the proof
   130	of lack of authorization.
   131	
   132	  Since January 1, 1978, all programs are protected by federal copyright laws
   133	without regard to copyright notice or registration with the Copyright Office and
   134	the state laws no longer apply.  The federal law "preempted" the state laws on
   135	that date.  But the federal rules apply across the board ONLY to works first
   136	"fixed" or "written" after that date.  However, improvements or modifications in
   137	one's own program can qualify for federal copyright protection under the new law
   138	and perhaps registration of their works as well as including the copyright
   139	notice somewhere in the program.
