   143	  It is obvious that most volunteer programmers do not have the finances or
   144	time, or inclination for that matter, to pursue a legal remedy in the courts.
   145	At the same time, they do not want the software they authored to be used by
   146	others for commercial gain without some control over its use.
   147	
   148	  I suggest that microcomputer software authors nation-wide form an organization
   149	similar to that of ASCAP or BMI, although on a smaller scale, to monitor
   150	improper uses of software donated to the hobbiest for personal use.  Only
   151	through concentrating the efforts and power of all authors can real protection
   152	be obtained.  Otherwise, the unscrupulous vendor is going to take his chances
   153	that the individual programmer will not or can not defend his copyright.
   154	
   155	  Such a group might be formed with the support of an active computer group like
   156	the NJ Amateur Computer Group or the Homebrew Computer Club in California.  Or
   157	it could be established independently if there were sufficient interest and an
   158	organizer could be found to do the necessary paperwork, collect the dues needed
   159	to provide a war chest, and hire the attorneys and other persons necessary.  It
   160	wouldn't have to be a full time job for anyone but it would have to be more than
   161	volunteer activity.
